Tachometer Refinement and Adjustment:¶

Step 1: gather experimental data from on modified sensor¶

Setup:¶


No Filter

Once the button is presses, 10000 samples are recorded, as well as the time duration. A magnet is moved infront of the sensor randomly to generate voltage fluctuations. It is assumed that the readings are close enough to equidistal in time that they can be modeled as such.

Note that as the magnet approaches the hall effect sensor that the voltage increases in a stochastic manner. Once the voltage cross the 500 mark, the fluctuations go away and the voltage increases to 5V which corresponds to ~ 1000 reading This indicates that once the magnetic field strength reaches a critical value, the sensor reads HIGH and then shoots up.

Problem Identification¶

The cause of the spikes when using an arduino based tachometer with a hall effect sensor is a bouce between the HIGH and LOW threasholds for an arduino digital pin. The fall appears to be faster that the rise

Proposed solution¶

Introduce a bandpass filter to smooth the bounce present in the LOW regions as the magnet is approaching/leaving the sensor

frequency analysis¶

# Number of sample points

# sample spacing
T = (x1[1] - x1[0])/1e6;  # dT in seconds 

x_data = np.linspace(0.0, N*T, N)
yf = fft(y1)
xf = np.linspace(0.0, 1.0/(2.0*T), N//2)
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.semilogy(xf, 2.0/N * np.abs(yf[0:N//2]))
plt.grid()
plt.show()

From the analysis it a appears that the desired cutoff frequency is around 1000 Hz, as there is noise beyond that

%matplotlib inline
# create bode plot to verify
sys = signal.TransferFunction(
    *symbolic.sym2poly(  
        # note the 1900 ohm resistor is what we actually have
        *sym.fraction(tf.subs({R: 1900, C: Cap})), 
        floater=True
    )
)

freq, mag, phase = signal.bode(sys)
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(2, 1)
llim, hlim = 4e3, 7e3
# setup mag plot
ax1.plot(freq, mag)
ax1.set_xlabel("freq [rad/s]")
ax1.set_ylabel("mag [dB]")
ax1.set_xlim([llim, hlim])
ax1.set_ylim([-5, 0])
ax1.grid()
# setup phase plot
ax2.plot(freq, phase)
ax2.set_xlabel("freq [rad/s]")
ax2.set_ylabel("phase [deg]");
ax2.set_xlim([llim, hlim])
ax2.grid();

from the plots above, we can see that using the 1900 ohm resistor we actually have access to, shifts the cutoff frequency to 5500 rad/s which is around 900 hz. This should be fine based on the FFT analysis above. The frequency of 1000 hz was chosen to simplify the analysis. As long as the cutoff frequency stays above 500 we should be fine.

# estimate range at which sensor can detect magnet
max_rise_time = max_time_delta*(50/360)
print(max_rise_time)

Note, that the rise time determined from the experimental setup is greater than the theoretical maximum rise time. The theoretical is 2.778 ms, while the experimental is 10 ms. This means that the rise time is a funciton of the magnet used, and the magnet that is actually used on the lathe currently is substansially stronger than the one used to collect data. Thus, the rise times collected from the experimental setup are most likely incorrect as the vibrations cause bouce that cuase the sensor currently in use to yeild extremely high RPM values speradically. It may be the case that the frequencies present in the signal are the same between the experimental setup and the actual setup. Thus an attempt will still be made to reduce the sensor noise and verify it's effectiveness.

Conclusions¶

Note the significant reduction in noise due to the addition of the filter. This has all but elemenated the bounce in the signal. To determine effectiveness and ensure that the time constant is not too high, data must be gathered in the working enviroment, with the actual magnets and rpm's in use.

If further testing reveals that the problem is not solved, a large reistor may be used to bring the flat signal around the 400 mark down close to zero, and an op-amp used to boost the second rise such that the system behave like that of a first order, and can be modeled as such.

Arduino Code¶

#include 

// define constants
constexpr int Vin = A1;
constexpr int btn = 8;
constexpr int LED = 9;
constexpr int reads = 10000;

// define variables
int val{};
unsigned long start_time{};
unsigned long end_time{};

void setup() {
  pinMode(Vin, INPUT);
  pinMode(btn, INPUT);
  pinMode(LED, OUTPUT);

  // ledDefault to off
  digitalWrite(LED, LOW);

  // highest baud rate for serial
  Serial.begin(115200);
}

void loop() {

  // wait for button press
  while (digitalRead(btn) != HIGH){
    delay(750);
  }

  // turn on the led
  digitalWrite(LED, HIGH);

  // prime the stream
  Serial.write(' ');

  // capture the start time
  start_time = micros();

  // send the readings to the terminal
  for (int i = 0; i < reads; i++){
    val = analogRead(Vin);
    Serial.write((char*)&val, (size_t)sizeof(val));
  }

  // capture the stop time
  end_time = micros();

  // turn off led
  digitalWrite(LED, LOW);

  // print out the times
  Serial.write((char*)&start_time, (size_t)sizeof(start_time));
  Serial.write((char*)&end_time, (size_t)sizeof(end_time));
}
